<hl>
<seg id=1> The Japanese Prime Minister hopes Kong Zhe will stay to continue his economic recovery plan. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Rutters Tokyo) Yesterday the Japanese Finance Minister Kong Zhe was facing the pressure for being asked to stay. </seg>
<seg id=3> He announced that he plans to resign in the near future last week. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> His leaving would have a negative impact on the plan for the Prime Minister's Independent Party and Xio Zhen's Democratic party to combine. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The senior officer thinks that the Democratic Party leadership appears to not be very stable, resulting in the combined party not being very strong </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> There are rumors outside the party that after Kong Zhe resigns the Democratic Parties Secretary will replace him. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Kong Zhe expressed last Friday that he might resign before the end of this year, however he didn't say the actual date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> At a news conference he said that "I can't say the date" </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is predicted that he will still be the Finance Minister until after the two week special meeting in the cabinet is complete. </seg>
<seg id=10> The cabinet meeting will be over on December 14th. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Xio Zhen's assistant secretary Lin Mo told the Japanese TV station that he believes the Prime Minister will ask 79 year old Kong Zhe to stay. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Lin Mo said that "I think Xio Zhen also wants him to stay to carry out his economic recovery plan." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Xio Zhen and Kong Zhe will meet. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said "because of his capabilities it is hard to find someone to replace him. </seg>
<seg id=15> Myself I hope he will stay to resume the countries economic recovery." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Xio Zhen made this statement after he read a related report about his possible plans to resign. He planed to talk with the Finance Minister. </seg>
</p>
